## Scope

This app uses **[argsbarg](https://www.npmjs.com/package/argsbarg)**. The `CliProgram` tree is the single source of truth for help, completions, MCP tools, and agent skills.

Package docs: `node_modules/argsbarg/readme.md`, `node_modules/argsbarg/docs/cli-program.md`, `node_modules/argsbarg/docs/mcp.md`.

## Defaults (basic apps)

- Set **`mcpServer: { enabled: true }`** on the program root when agents should call the CLI over MCP.
- **Do not add `mcpTool` on every leaf** — ArgsBarg exposes leaves automatically with descriptions and `inputSchema` derived from the schema.
- Write **`description`** on the root, each command, and each option/positional for `-h`; those strings feed MCP and skills.

## Inline schema (default)

Keep **`CliProgram` and leaf params inline** (`options`, `positionals`, `handler`) unless extraction is justified — the schema should be readable at a glance.

**Extract when:** shared options (`DRY_RUN_OPTION`), shared `mcpTool` spreads, or a command factory because the handler is large (Ink + headless dispatch). **Do not extract** thin wrappers that only move static schema to another file.

Use **`satisfies CliProgram`** on the root or on command factories.

## Leaf commands (`CliLeaf`)

- One clear **`description`** per leaf (verb + object; no UI jargon unless CLI-only).
- Use standard option names when semantics match: **`yes`**, **`dry-run`**, **`json`**
- Write option **`description`** text for agents (e.g. "Skip confirmation; use for non-interactive runs.")

## `mcpTool` — escape hatches (rare)

**Default: omit `mcpTool`.** ArgsBarg exposes tool names, descriptions, and `inputSchema` from the schema.

Reach for `mcpTool` only when the schema cannot express the constraint. **Before adding an escape hatch, fix the underlying CLI design** if the motivation is an anti-pattern:

| Temptation | Prefer instead |
| --- | --- |
| `mcpTool.description` explaining custom flags | Rename to **`yes`**, **`dry-run`**, or **`json`** when semantics match; describe them on the option |
| `mcpTool.description` saying "pass `--json`" | Implement headless/`--json` in the **handler**; ensure the option exists on the leaf |
| `mcpTool.enabled: false` because prompts block MCP | Add **`--yes`** / flag resolution so MCP can run headless; hide only if headless is impossible |
| `mcpTool.description` duplicating help with MCP caveats | Rewrite leaf **`description`** and option text for agents; one description for both audiences |
| `enabled: false` to hide incomplete commands | Finish headless path or split into a dedicated scriptable subcommand |

Legitimate escape hatches:

| Field | When |
| --- | --- |
| `enabled: false` | Truly CLI-only (browser, TUI with no headless equivalent, internal debug) |
| `requiresEnv: ["VAR"]` | Secrets — cannot live in the schema |
| `description: "..."` | **Genuine** MCP limitation that cannot be fixed in schema/handler (e.g. streaming/`--watch` not supported on the wire yet) |

If you add `mcpTool`, leave a short comment in code **why** a schema/handler fix was not enough.

## Headless-capable handlers

Simple leaves (stdout only) need no branching. **If a handler can mount Ink, prompt, or open a browser, it must also support a scriptable fast path** for MCP, non-TTY CLI, and `--json` / `--dry-run` / `--yes`.

- **One headless path** serves MCP + piped CLI + explicit flags — not separate MCP handlers.
- **Mutators:** `--yes` (and/or `--dry-run`); use `shouldRunHeadlessWithYes` + `requireYesInNonTty`.
- **Queries:** optional `--json`; use `shouldRunHeadless` + `wantsExplicitJson`.
- **Positionals:** use `shouldRunHeadlessWithPositionals` so empty argv does not auto-headless into errors.
- **Resolve from flags first** — wizards are TTY-only; flags must be enough for agents.
- **`ctx.invocation === "mcp"`** — only for wire-specific behavior (pipe subprocess stdout, reject `--watch`), not duplicate business logic.
- **`mcpTool.enabled: false`** only when headless is truly impossible.

```typescript
// Mutating pattern (sketch)
requireYesInNonTty(yes, "Example: myapp cmd … --yes", dryRun);
if (shouldRunHeadlessWithYes(ctx, { yes, hasRequiredArgs, dryRun })) {
  /* stdout/stderr only */ return;
}
await renderInteractive(/* … */);
```

See `node_modules/argsbarg/docs/cli-program.md` for full examples.

## Handlers

- Same handler serves CLI and MCP; headless-capable when the command may be interactive (see **Headless-capable handlers** above).
- Use **`ctx.invocation`** (`"cli"` | `"mcp"`) only for wire-specific subprocess/TTY behavior.
- Prefer ArgsBarg headless helpers over ad-hoc `process.stdin.isTTY` checks.
- Do not declare reserved root commands: `completion`, `install`, `mcp`, `version`, `docs`, `update`.

## Types

Annotate the program with **`satisfies CliProgram`** (or `: CliProgram`). Root must have **`key`**, **`version`**, **`description`**; routers use **`commands`**, leaves use **`handler`**.
